name: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3550
Reason: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate has a melting point influenced by its structural components relative to the base melting point of benzene, which is around 5°C. The methyl group introduces a rigid structure, which can participate in hydrogen bonding and increase the melting point by approximately +5°C. The oxo group introduces additional rigid structures that can participate in dipole interactions and potentially hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +10°C. The androstane ring introduces additional rigid structures that can participate in dipole interactions and potentially hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +30°C. The acetate group introduces a carbonyl functional group, which can participate in dipole interactions and hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +20°C. The methyl ester group introduces a more asymmetric structure, reducing the crystal lattice stability, which might decrease the melting point by approximately -10°C. Summing up these changes: The methyl group at +5°C, the oxo group at +10°C, the androstane ring at +30°C, and the acetate group at +20°C.
